│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe reproducer shows InstCombine    │
│ transforming a rotate-left funnel shift (fshl %or, %or, 1) into a form where  │
│ the 2nd operand is replaced by a constant (-2). Subsequent passes then shrink │
│ the constant feeding the rotate logic (the 'or disjoint' op) because the      │
│ demanded bits analysis now sees the operands as independent, ultimately       │
│ producing an fshl value outside the original range metadata, making the       │
│ result poison per Alive2. The incorrect transformation is introduced in       │
│ SimplifyDemandedUseBits() for the fshl intrinsic when the code interprets a   │
│ rotate pattern (equal operands) and replaces one operand with a constant      │
│ formed from Known.One bits. This replacement is not semantics-preserving      │
│ unless the entire operand is known constant. Here only a slice of demanded    │
│ bits for each operand contribution is proven, not the entire rotated value,   │
│ so the transform is unsound.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first change is: │
│ fshl %or, %or, 1 -> fshl %or, -2, 1. This occurs before any other             │
│ modifications. After that, the 'or disjoint' constant is progressively        │
│ changed (-2 -> 2147483646 -> 126) via ShrinkDemandedConstant because demanded │
│ masks for the %or uses are now narrower (due to the split operand roles after │
│ replacement). This cascade would not occur if the original rotate form were   │
│ preserved. The trunc gets nuw later because the transformed range appears     │
│ unsigned, but the range metadata becomes invalid since the actual fshl result │
│ can be 0x000000FD (253) instead of a signed negative value in [-4,1]. Alive2  │
│ flags this as 'Target is more poisonous than source'.\n\n3. Root Cause        │
│ Analysis:\nIn InstCombineSimplifyDemanded.cpp (lines ~1047–1063), within case │
│ Intrinsic::fshl/fshr handling, there's a special block for the rotate case    │
│ (operands equal) that:\n  a) Computes known bits for the operand.\n  b) If    │
│ the demanded mask slice for the left or right portion is a subset of          │
│ Known.Zero | Known.One, it replaces that operand with a constant of Known.One │
│ bits.\nThis logic misinterprets partial known bits of the operand as license  │
│ to substitute a constant operand. For a rotate, the result's bits are a       │
│ permutation of the original full operand bits. Replacing one copy with a      │
│ constant of only the bits known one changes semantics whenever any            │
│ non-demanded slice later becomes demanded by other transformations, or when   │
│ cross-slice dependencies exist (which they do here—bit movement between       │
│ halves via rotation). Because the initial demanded masks (DemandedMaskLHS =   │
│ full minus top bit; DemandedMaskRHS = only top bit) are artificially          │
│ partitioned, the code decides it's safe, but global demanded mask was all     │
│ ones (SimplifyDemandedInstructionBits), so the replacement must be            │
│ semantics-preserving unconditionally. It is not, unless the entire operand    │
│ value is constant. This violates correctness and enables further unsound      │
│ shrinking of upstream constants.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nEdit lines   │
│ 1047–1063 in InstCombineSimplifyDemanded.cpp to remove the unsafe             │
│ rotate-specific operand replacement. Replace the rotate branch with logic     │
│ that treats both operands identically (just compute known bits) without       │
│ modifying operands. New block:\n  } else { // fshl/fshr with identical        │
│ operands is a rotate; do not mutate operand based on partial demanded         │
│ slices.\n    // Just compute known bits once; both operands are the same      │
│ value.\n    LHSKnown = computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, I);\n    │
│ RHSKnown = LHSKnown;\n  }\nRationale: This preserves original rotate          │
│ semantics and still allows proper known bits propagation without introducing  │
│ an unsound substitution. If a future enhancement wants to replace the entire  │
│ rotate with a constant, it must first prove the operand itself is fully       │
│ constant (all bits known), not just slices.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy eliminating │
│ the unsafe operand replacement in the rotate case, we prevent InstCombine     │
│ from breaking the equivalence of the fshl intrinsic and from enabling         │
│ subsequent ShrinkDemandedConstant calls to alter upstream constants           │
│ incorrectly. This keeps range metadata valid and avoids producing poison      │
│ where the source was non-poison. The fix is localized, conservative, and      │
│ maintains existing known-bits inference without risking semantic              │
│ changes.\n"})                                                                 │
